ight instead. He repeats until all the stones are stuck. Let $p_{k}$ be the probability that at the end of the process there are exactly $k$ stones in the right half. Evaluate $$\\frac{p_{n-1}-p_{n-2}+p_{n-3}-\\ldots+p_{3}-p_{2}+p_{1}}{p_{n-1}+p_{n-2}+p_{n-3}+\\ldots+p_{3}+p_{2}+p_{1}}$$ in terms of $n$.", "domain": ["Mathematics -> Applied Mathematics -> Statistics -> Probability -> Other"], "difficulty": 5.0, "source": "HMMT_2", "answer_gt": "\\frac{1}{n-1}", "model_generation": "Skipping.", "parsed_answer": null, "outcome": "skipped", "score_delta": 0, "cumulative_score": -38}, {"step_number": 10, "idx": 1718, "problem": "Find the smallest positive integer $b$ such that $1111_{b}$ ( 1111 in base $b$) is a perfect square. If no such $b$ exists, write \"No solution\".", "domain": ["Mathematics -> Number Theory -> Factorization"], "difficulty": 4.5, "source": "HMMT_11", "answer_gt": "7", "model_generation": "\\(1111_b=b^3+b^2+b+1=(b+1)(b^2+1)\\).\n\nWe need \\((b+1)(b^2+1)\\) to be a perfect square. Note\n\\[\n\\gcd(b+1,b^2+1)=\\gcd(b+1,\\,b^2+1-(b-1)(b+1))=\\gcd(b+1,2),\n\\]\nso the gcd is \\(1\\) if \\(b\\) is even and \\(2\\) if \\(b\\) is odd.\n\n- If \\(b\\) is even, the factors are coprime, so each must be a square: \\(b+1\\) square and \\(b^2+1\\) square. But \\(b^2<b^2+1<(b+1)^2\\) for \\(b\\ge1\\), so \\(b^2+1\\) cannot be a square. No even \\(b\\).\n\n- If \\(b\\) is odd, write \\(b+1=2u,\\ b^2+1=2v\\) with \\(\\gcd(u,v)=1\\). Then \\(1111_b=4uv\\) is a square, so \\(uv\\) must be a square; with \\(\\gcd(u,v)=1\\), both \\(u\\) and \\(v\\) are squares. Thus \\(b+1=2u\\) is twice a square and \\(b^2+1=2v\\) is twice a square. Check smallest odd \\(b\\ge2\\):\n  - \\(b=3:\\ 1111_3=40\\) not square.\n  - \\(b=5:\\ 1111_5=156\\) not square.\n  - \\(b=7:\\ 1111_7=400=20^2\\) works.\n\nSo the smallest \\(b\\) is \\(\\boxed{7}\\).", "parsed_answer": "7", "outcome": "correct", "score_delta": 1, "cumulative_score": -37}, {"step_number": 11, "idx": 1857, "problem": 